            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is added sugar?</h2>
              <p>
                Added sugar refers to sugars and syrups that are added to foods
                and drinks during processing, preparation, or at the table. This
                includes table sugar, brown sugar, honey, maple syrup, agave,
                high-fructose corn syrup, and other caloric sweeteners.
              </p>
              <p>
                It does <strong>not</strong> include the sugars that are
                naturally present in whole fruits, vegetables, and plain milk.
                However, fruit juices, smoothies, and many processed foods can
                contribute a large amount of <em>free sugars</em>, which behave
                similarly to added sugars in the body.
              </p>

              <h3>Why limiting added sugar matters</h3>
              <p>High intakes of added sugar are associated with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Higher total calorie intake and weight gain over time</li>
                <li>
                  Increased risk of type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease
                </li>
                <li>
                  Higher triglycerides and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease
                </li>
                <li>
                  Dental caries (tooth decay), especially with frequent sugary
                  drinks
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Major organizations such as the World Health Organization (WHO),
                American Heart Association (AHA), and national dietary
                guidelines recommend keeping added or free sugars to a small
                fraction of daily energy intake.
              </p>

              <h2>How the added sugar calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your daily added sugar intake in three
                steps:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>You enter your typical daily foods and drinks</strong>
                  and their grams of added sugar per serving.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The tool
                  <strong>sums the total grams and calories</strong> from added
                  sugar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It then
                  <strong>compares your intake to guideline limits</strong>
                  based on your daily calories and sex.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Key formulas</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li>
                    <code>Added sugar kcal = grams of added sugar × 4</code>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code
                      >% of energy from added sugar = (added sugar kcal ÷ total
                      daily kcal) × 100</code
                    >
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>WHO 10% limit (g) = (0.10 × daily kcal) ÷ 4</code>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>WHO 5% target (g) = (0.05 × daily kcal) ÷ 4</code>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Guideline reference values used</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>WHO 10% limit:</strong> free sugars &lt;10% of total
                  energy intake.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>WHO 5% target:</strong> a further reduction to &lt;5%
                  of energy for additional health benefits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>AHA upper limit (adults):</strong> about 25 g/day for
                  most women and 36 g/day for most men.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Children:</strong> many pediatric guidelines recommend
                  &lt;25 g/day of added sugar.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <h3>1. Total grams and calories from added sugar</h3>
              <p>
                The first panel shows your
                <strong>total grams of added sugar</strong> and the
                corresponding <strong>calories from added sugar</strong>. This
                is the sum of all items you entered.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Percentage of daily calories</h3>
              <p>
                The second panel shows the
                <strong>percentage of your daily calories</strong> that comes
                from added sugar. This is the key number used by WHO and many
                national guidelines.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>&lt;5%:</strong> aligned with WHO’s more protective
                  target.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>5–10%:</strong> within the general WHO limit, but
                  consider reducing if possible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>&gt;10%:</strong> above recommended levels – worth
                  reviewing your main sources of sugar.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Guideline comparison badge</h3>
              <p>
                The status badge summarizes how your intake compares to the WHO
                and AHA limits:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Within guideline:</strong> below both WHO 10% and AHA
                  limit for your profile.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Above AHA but below WHO 10%:</strong> moderate intake;
                  reducing sugary drinks and desserts can help.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Above WHO 10%:</strong> high intake; consider more
                  substantial changes.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Common hidden sources of added sugar</h2>
              <p>
                Added sugar is not only in obvious sweets. Frequent contributors
                include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Soft drinks, energy drinks, sweetened teas, and flavored
                  coffees
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fruit juices and juice drinks (even “100% juice” is high in
                  free sugars)
                </li>
                <li>Breakfast cereals and granola bars</li>
                <li>Flavored yogurts and dairy desserts</li>
                <li>
                  Ketchup, barbecue sauce, salad dressings, and other condiments
                </li>
                <li>Packaged breads, buns, and baked goods</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Practical tips to reduce added sugar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Switch your drinks first.</strong> Replace sugary
                  drinks with water, sparkling water, or unsweetened tea/coffee.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose whole fruit over juice.</strong> Whole fruit
                  provides fiber and is more filling.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check labels for “Added Sugars”.</strong> Many
                  countries now list added sugars in grams per serving.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Buy plain versions.</strong> Choose plain yogurt or
                  oatmeal and add a small amount of fruit yourself.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Watch portion sizes.</strong> Even small reductions in
                  serving size can meaningfully lower daily sugar.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Limit sweets to specific occasions.</strong> Making
                  desserts an occasional treat helps keep daily intake low.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of this calculator</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Relies on the accuracy of the grams of added sugar you enter.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not distinguish between added and naturally occurring
                  sugars if they are not separated on the label.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not account for individual medical conditions or
                  personalized nutrition needs.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this tool as a starting point for awareness. For tailored
                advice, consult a registered dietitian or your healthcare
                provider.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is “no added sugar” the same as sugar-free?</h3>
              <p>
                Not necessarily. “No added sugar” means no sugars were added
                during processing, but the product can still contain
                <strong>naturally occurring sugars</strong> (for example, in
                fruit or milk). “Sugar-free” usually means the product contains
                less than a certain small amount of sugar per serving (often
                &lt;0.5 g), but may contain low- or no-calorie sweeteners.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I need to avoid all added sugar?</h3>
              <p>
                For most healthy people, the goal is
                <strong>limiting</strong> added sugar, not eliminating it
                completely. Occasional sweets can fit into a balanced diet if
                your overall intake stays within recommended limits and you
                prioritize nutrient-dense foods.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I track my added sugar?</h3>
              <p>
                Many people find it helpful to track for a few typical days
                (including a weekend day) to understand their usual intake.
                After that, you can re-check whenever your habits change or if
                you are working on specific health goals.
              </p>
